[[Category:Streets in Madrid]] [[Category:Art gallery districts]] [[Category:Museo del Prado]] [[Category:Bien de Interés Cultural landmarks in Madrid]] [[Category:Paseo del Prado]]

"'''Shepherd's Guide'''" is the title given to several books, that were published to help [[Shepherd|shepherds]] identify stray herds. The books depict patterns of [[Lamb marking|sheep marking]], in the ear and on the wool, and name their owner with his residence.

One of the earliest ''Shepherd's Guide'' was prepared for parts of [[Cumberland]] by Joseph Walker, in 1817.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.longsleddale.co.uk/fullrecs/SMITf.htm|title=Shepherd's Guides - Longsleddale|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> Hosgson's 1849 ''Guide'' was delivered to a list of subscribers,<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.pastpresented.ukart.com/eskdale/sheep/marks.htm | title = SHEEP MARKS AND THE "SHEPHERD'S GUIDE"}}</ref>, while ''Gate's new shepherd's guide for Cumberland, Westmoreland, and Lancashire'', of 1879, has numerous pages of advertisements. While all of those feature a detailed engraving of sheep (repeated with different marks), the books from the late 19th and 20th centuries have a [[Line art|line sketch]]. Some were designed as pocket-books, and others were bigger. The later books are attributed to various farmer associations, and cover a wider perimeter.

The books are useful as a [[genealogical]] and [[local history]] resource, and as [[Collectable|collectibles]].<ref>[[Antiques Roadshow]], series 37 episode 19.</ref>

